The paper deals with the complexity of the minus-domination problem in graphs, which is a topic in graph theory and combinatorics. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves the study of graph parameters such as degeneracy and rankwidth, which are topics in discrete mathematics, suggesting that cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) is another likely category. The paper also mentions the polynomial complexity of the problem for strongly chordal graphs, which are a subclass of perfect graphs, indicating that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is a possible category. The paper also involves the study of splitgraphs, which are a subclass of chordal graphs, suggesting that cs.GT (Graph Theory) is another possible category. Finally, the paper deals with the fixed-parameter tractability of the problem, which is a topic in computational geometry, indicating that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is a possible category.
